decrease in the number of Android apps on the Google Play Store would be concerning if it wasn\u0026#39;t actually a good thing. Because Android owners are ultimately benefitting from this.\u003c/p\u003e    \u003ch2 id=\"why-fewer-android-apps-is-a-good-thing\"\u003e\n                        Why Fewer Android Apps Is a Good Thing\n               \u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe key is Google\u0026#39;s attempt to foster quality over quantity, with the company making concerted efforts to clean up the Play Store. In July 2024, Google announced that it woiuld be \u003ca href=\"https://support.google.com/googleplay/android-developer/answer/14993590?sjid=15903831026892834828-EU\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eraising its minimum quality requirements for Android apps\u003c/a\u003e, and there have been other policies enacted too.\u003c/p\u003e    \n\u003cp\u003eThese include an expanded set of verification standards, new developer accounts being required to test their apps, and humans spending more time reviewing apps before they were published to the Google Play Store.\u003c/p\u003e    \n\u003cp\u003eSo, while on the surface, Android owners may be feeling aggrieved that there are fewer Android apps to choose from, what\u0026#39;s left should be of a higher quality, with the spammy and scammy apps having been purged.\u003c/p\u003e            \n    \n                    \n                        \n    \n    \n                                        \n    \n        \n    \n        \n                \n        \n    \u003cdiv data-include-community-rating=\"false\" id=\"215f-4dac-988577ec10df\" data-nosnippet=\"\"\u003e\n        \n        \n                        \t                \n\t\t\u003ca href=\"https://www.makeuseof.com/malicious-google-play-store-app-stole-70000/\"\u003e\n\t\n\t\u003cdiv data-img-url=\"https://static1.makeuseofimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/hand-holding-smartphone-with-malware.jpg\" data-modal-id=\"single-image-m